 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Nikodamos fils de Prato<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">médès</supplied>, Alexiklès fils d'Euphranôr, Hypertélès fils d'Eukartès, Pratomédès fils de Kallippos,
            Ammônios fils de Theukhrestos, Mnastoklès fils de Strat<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>, Pollidas fils de Kléôn, Etearkhos <supplied reason="lost">fils d'Untel</supplied>,
            <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Nikodamos son of Prato<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">medes</supplied>, Alexikles son of Euphranor, Hyperteles son of Eukartes, Pratomedes son of Kallippos,
            Ammonios son of Theuchrestos, Mnastokles son of Strat<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>, Pollidas son of Kleon, Etearchos <supplied reason="lost">son of So-and-so</supplied>,
            <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Nikodamos figlio di Prato<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">medes</supplied>, Alexikles figlio di Euphranor, Hyperteles figlio di Eukartes, Pratomedes figlio di Kallippos,
            Ammonios figlio di Theuchrestos, Mnastokles figlio di Strat<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>, Pollidas figlio di Kleon, Etearchos <supplied reason="lost">figlio del tale</supplied>,
            <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                <p>The provenance of this fragment was given by Pugliese Carratelli from Oliverio's papers similarly to that of <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr100200</ref> and is plausibly identified 
                as some point in Apollo's sanctuary (see also <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>351</citedRange>, footnote 2</bibl>).</p>
                <p>The lettering allows to date this list with confidence more or less in the middle of the fourth century. A more precise date is provided by Rosamilia on prosopographical grounds. This list is very similar to lists of military officers 
                    like for instance <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr014800</ref>. A Kallippos son of Pratomedes is mentioned there (a.ii.32) as commander of a company of four-horse chariots, whereas
                a Kleon son of Pollidas is mentioned as a damiergos in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr012400</ref> and also without context in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr107300</ref>. All three inscriptions may be dated around 335/330 BC. So the fathers 
                    of the two men might be mentioned here at lines 4 and 7.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
